{"type":"message","id":"9d0f06af","parentId":"a2799a4a","timestamp":"2026-03-23T13:12:07.843Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The honest answer is: I don't have full visibility into my own context boundaries.\n\nWhat I think happened with the `rag/` corpus specifically:\n\nThe RAG pipeline was built during a different phase (Mar 17–19). When I shifted to the LinkedIn/X/Facebook scrape on Mar 21–22, `nava-corpus/` became the active working directory. `rag/` was a separate namespace — same workspace, different purpose. When you asked about the blog corpus, I looked in `nava-corpus/` because that's where recent corpus work lives. When I didn't find it, I extended \"not in this directory\" to \"doesn't exist.\"\n\nThe fix isn't one thing — it's several:\n\n**Immediate things we can do:**\n\n1. **Update MEMORY.md** with the full corpus map — `nava-corpus/` for social, `rag/` for blog. When I forget a location, the map tells me where to look.\n\n2. **Before answering corpus questions, search both directories** — make it a habit to check `rag/` even when `nava-corpus/` is the obvious answer.\n\n3. **Check memory files for project history** — the Mar 17–19 RAG work should be logged in `memory/2026-03-17.md` or similar. If it was there, I didn't read it before answering.\n\n**The harder underlying problem:**\n\nI'm session-scoped. Each session starts fresh with only what I've written to memory files. If the RAG work was logged but I didn't read that file at session startup, the knowledge is invisible to me. That's not fixable without making memory files more reliably complete and read at startup.\n\nWant me to write that corpus map to MEMORY.md now so it's there next session?"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":46333,"output":762,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":47095,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1774271527841}}
